Over the last 13 years, Sarah Harrelson has been building Cultured Magazine=
 into the kind of new-look, art-focused media company that speaks to the br=
oad tent of today=E2=80=99s art world. Open any one of her oversized issues=
 and you=E2=80=99ll find a magazine from yesteryear, with pages and pages a=
nd pages of fashion and luxury ads=E2=80=94Gucci, Herm=C3=A8s, Chanel, Vale=
ntino, Saint Laurent, Rolex, Van Cleef, etcetera=E2=80=94before the table o=
f contents. That=E2=80=99s followed by front-of-the-book items, and a featu=
re well using familiar magazine tropes: an annual list of young artists to =
watch; film or food crossover issues; or a Cult 100 list mixing celebrities=
 (Gwyneth Paltrow, Bowen Yang, Venus Williams, Alicia Keys) with art world =
luminaries (Tyler Mitchell, Mickalene Thomas, Marc Payot, Jason
Farago, Peter Marino) to create a shared but specific sense of glamor that =
places the art world=E2=80=99s figures at center stage.

Harrelson has captured an audience of 50,000 subscribers the old-fashioned =
magazine way, by bootstrapping her editorial ideas (and her own money) into=
 a long-standing relationship with advertisers who want to reach the art wo=
rld=E2=80=99s actual participants. =E2=80=9CA lot of those people have been=
 running with me for eight years,=E2=80=9D Harrelson told me as we sat down=
 at Sant Ambroeus, in Nolita, to discuss the trajectory of her business. =
=E2=80=9CHerm=C3=A8s, Cartier=E2=80=94I got those accounts when it was me a=
nd one other person.=E2=80=9D

In the 20th Century, the art world was dominated by just a few magazines, w=
hich not only informed the curious and faithful but also acted as a trainin=
g ground for writers, editors, and even curators who would go on to hold in=
fluential institutional positions. Art in America and ARTnews were the hous=
e
organs of American art as it ascended from a backwater to the white-hot cen=
ter of Modern art in the postwar era. Artforum, which emerged from the 1960=
s, evolved from a bastion of hipster cool under the late Ingrid Sischy, to =
become a hybrid of ivory tower analysis surrounded by a hyper-commercial ca=
talog of gallery ads.

Mainstream, mass-market magazines have always dabbled in art coverage, too.=
 But as the internet gobbled up the audience for print, the art world began=
 to lose its sense of having a common ground, a place where artists could t=
ake center stage but collectors, curators, and art advisors could also be f=
eatured, flattered, and shown off. Artforum, which just hired a new editor,=
 has yet to find a recognizably new voice. Sotheby=E2=80=99s, for its part,=
 will launch a new iteration of its magazine early next month. But even wit=
h the intention of fusing the worlds of art, celebrity, and fashion, the pu=
blication will have to find the right
connection to Sotheby=E2=80=99s client base, whose only shared experience i=
s having transacted with the luxury retail giant. Harrelson has already mad=
e that connection with her audience=E2=80=94and her momentum only seems to =
be growing.

