          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Born in New Jersey,=
 Harrelson found her way to Miami in the early 2000s just as the city was b=
ecoming an international art hub, and found a job running the Home and Desi=
gn section for the <i>Miami Herald</i>. After seven years at the <i>Herald<=
/i>, Harrelson opted to help launch a design magazine for <i>Ocean Drive</i=
>, which included creating a magazine for Art Basel. <br/><br/>In 2011, she=
 decided to strike out with a magazine of her own. <i>Cultured</i> began wi=
th two issues a year, funded in part by Harrelson=E2=80=99s other jobs, all=
owing her to reinvest her first $30,000 in ad revenue into growing the busi=
ness. When I asked about her spouse, she told me he was an interior designe=
r, before confessing that she was trying hard not to make a joke by announc=
ing that, =E2=80=9CNo, he doesn=E2=80=99t work in finance!=E2=80=9D<br/><br=
/>It=E2=80=99s hard to separate the early
success of <i>Cultured</i>, which has since expanded to five issues a year,=
 from the transformation of Miami, itself, from the capital of South and Ce=
ntral America with its own recognizable design aesthetic into the internati=
onal wealth haven it has become today. =E2=80=9CThe magazine was never <i>a=
bout</i> Miami,=E2=80=9D Harrelson pointed out, even if she was in Miami at=
 the time. But, she added, the <i>demographic</i> was extremely interesting=
 to brands. She recounted calling advertisers to tell them she was getting =
distribution in Switzerland, at Art Basel, and =E2=80=9Cthey didn=E2=80=99t=
 really care at all.=E2=80=9D They were already happy with the new crowd sh=
e was reaching in Miami. The city also enabled Harrelson to open a live eve=
nts arm, now her second largest source of revenue. Gucci, for instance, ask=
ed <i>Cultured </i>to collaborate on a party celebrating the opening of the=
ir flagship store in town. Harrelson, intimidated by the ask, assumed Gucci=
 wanted her to deliver big spenders.
Instead, she recalled, =E2=80=9CThey said, =E2=80=98We want curators, we wa=
nt artists.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Harrelson wanted to expand. So, in =
2019, she launched a second magazine in Los Angeles. It didn=E2=80=99t surv=
ive the pandemic, but Harrelson and her husband decided to move to L.A. any=
way. Her advertisers stuck with her. =E2=80=9CMy main goal at the beginning=
 was really just to be accepted by the art world,=E2=80=9D she told me, pro=
ud that she had focused on under-represented voices (pre-2020) and curators=
, =E2=80=9Cin a significant way.=E2=80=9D Then, the content began to evolve=
 as she was able to increase her budget for writers, design, and photograph=
y. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t cover celebrity until 2019,=E2=80=9D she said.=
 =E2=80=9CBut the core of the content is really the same. There=E2=80=99s j=
ust more of it.=E2=80=9D <br/></td>
