          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">For someone who cam=
e up working at fashion and design magazines, Harrelson is down-to-earth an=
d earnest. =E2=80=9CWhen I started the magazine, I would look at the way <i=
>W</i> and <i>Vogue </i>would cover artists,=E2=80=9D she told me. =E2=80=
=9CAnd, it=E2=80=99s not that there was anything wrong with it, but I alway=
s wanted to present the artists as they were in the studio, you know, witho=
ut a team of hair and makeup and stylists.=E2=80=9D She=E2=80=99s also part=
icularly proud of helping open the closed ranks of the art world to a more =
diverse set of collectors. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve had collectors walk up to =
me and say, =E2=80=98I=E2=80=99m a 30-year-old person of color, I=E2=80=99v=
e walked into a gallery and basically been ignored, your magazine gave me t=
he courage to do this,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Harrelson said. A forthcoming issu=
e features interviews with both visual artist <b>George Condo </b>and rappe=
r <b>Travis Scott</b>,
and she=E2=80=99s truly excited to see what the conversation produces. That=
 may be <i>Cultured</i>=E2=80=99s greatest strength: an unbridled enthusias=
m for artists, dealers, collectors, and how they all fit into a broader cul=
ture.<br/><br/>Her beachhead in Los Angeles may not have yielded its own ma=
gazine, but Harrelson hasn=E2=80=99t given up on expansion. In recent years=
, she began producing broadsheet versions of <i>Cultured</i> that are distr=
ibuted where the art world congregates during the year=E2=80=94there=E2=80=
=99s a supplement for Art Basel in Miami Beach, two for the Hamptons, and n=
ow one for Aspen=E2=80=99s early August art rendezvous. This year, Harrelso=
n organized a series of talks at Anderson Ranch featuring artists, critics,=
 collectors, and even Harrelson herself as an interviewer. <br/><br/>When I=
 asked where she might go next, Harrelson mentioned Mexico City, a growing =
art capital with its own well-established art fair in February, Zona Maco, =
and numerous gallery and collector exhibition
spaces. There=E2=80=99s also several European cities where <i>Cultured</i> =
has promising penetration through subscriptions and newsstand sales. Meanwh=
ile, Harrelson has been gradually expanding her digital business, creating =
a web-only subscription as well as higher priced tiers for print and the V.=
I.P. Cultured Club to cultivate a passionate audience she can deliver to bu=
siness partners. There=E2=80=99s also an Instagram account, of course, with=
 352,000 followers, far behind <i>Artforum</i> and <i>ARTnews</i>=E2=80=99s=
 million-plus follower counts, but not out of the hunt given those two bran=
ds=E2=80=99 long head start in name recognition. <br/><br/>Besides being a =
magazine with a more organic connection with art world audiences, <i>Cultur=
ed</i> has the advantage of not being an incumbent in the art media. Harrel=
son has been able to build her business with grit, determination, and a goo=
d sense of where to spend her money for the most effect. With so many deep-=
pocketed corporate competitors=E2=80=94we
haven=E2=80=99t even discussed the gallery-sponsored magazines=E2=80=94<i>C=
ultured</i>=E2=80=99s rise has been an unexpected but welcome surprise. <br=
/></td>
         </tr>
